**HTML (HyperText Markup Language)**

HTML forms the foundation of any web page, serving as the skeleton that structures the content. It uses elements such as paragraphs, headings, images, and links to define the layout and organization of the content. By creating a structured framework, HTML provides the basic building blocks for a web page, allowing browsers to render and display the content correctly.

**The Origin of HTML**

This document serves as an introduction to HTML (HyperText Markup Language), the essential building block for front-end development. As the first language you will encounter in your coding journey, understanding HTML is crucial for structuring and organizing content on web pages. This class will cover the basics of HTML, its history, and its evolution, preparing you for the exciting world of web development.  
![][image2]

**Understanding HTML**

HTML stands for HyperText Markup Language, which is a markup language that defines the structure and presentation of raw text. Unlike programming languages, markup languages do not involve logic or computation; they simply organize and format text to be displayed correctly. HTML allows computers to interpret and present text in a structured format.

**Key Concepts of HTML**

* **Markup Language:** A markup language is a type of computer language that defines the structure and presentation of raw text. It organizes and formats text to ensure it displays correctly on web pages.

![][image3]

* **HTML Elements:** In HTML, raw text is wrapped in HTML elements, which are tags that help the computer understand how to display the content. This enables the creation of well-structured and visually organized web pages.  
* **HyperText:** HyperText refers to text displayed on a computer or device that provides access to other text through links, commonly known as hyperlinks. You've likely clicked on a few hyperlinks on your way to this course.

**HTML's Creator: A Look at Its History**

**HTML** was created by Tim Berners-Lee in 1993 to define the structure of a web page. Without it, you wouldn’t be able to organize text or add images or videos to your pages. HTML is the beginning of everything you need to know to make your first website.

**Sir Tim Berners-Lee** is an English computer scientist popularly known for his development of the World Wide Web in 1989\.

While working at the European Organization for Nuclear Research (CERN) in the European Particle Physics Laboratory, Berners-Lee saw the need for a system that would share information amongst researchers globally. With this motivation, Tim Berners-Lee facilitated the first transmission between an HTTP client and server. Berners-Lee then developed the first web browser in 1990\. With these milestones met, Berners-Lee developed the first-ever website, [https://info.cern.ch./](https://info.cern.ch./)

In 1993, Berners-Lee wrote the very first version of HTML (HyperText Markup Language), the standard markup language for web pages.

![][image4]

| Version | Year | Key Features |
| :---- | :---- | :---- |
| **HTML 1.0** | 1993 | First version of HTML. Capable of formatting text, adding links, and creating lists. |
| **HTML 2.0** | 1995 | Introduced more tags and attributes. Added support for forms and tables, setting the foundation for more complex web pages. |
| **HTML 3.2** | 1997 | Introduced new tags like \<font\> and \<center\>. |
| **HTML 4.01** | 1999 | Standardized many features. Introduced CSS for styling. Supported scripting languages like JavaScript. Laid the groundwork for separating content from design. |
| **HTML5** | 2014 | Introduced new elements for multimedia, such as \<video\> and \<audio\>. Enhanced support for mobile devices. Offered powerful APIs for building interactive applications. |

Learning HTML is the first step in creating websites. As you continue learning, you can layer HTML with CSS and JavaScript to create visually compelling and dynamic websites. But for now, we’re going to focus on how to add and modify basic content on a page, like text, images, and videos.

 **Basic HTML Structure**

An HTML document is organized into a structured format that helps browsers render web pages correctly. Here’s a breakdown of the key components:

Code Example:

\<\!DOCTYPE html\>

\<html\>

  \<head\>

	\<title\>My First Webpage\</title\>

  \</head\>

  \<body\>

	\<p\>Hello, welcome to my first webpage\!\</p\>

  \</body\>

\</html\>

**Document Declaration and Root Element**

\<\!DOCTYPE html\>**:**

* **Purpose**: This declaration defines the document type and version of HTML (HTML5 in this case). It helps the browser understand how to interpret and render the page correctly.  
* **Placement**: It is placed at the very top of the HTML document before the \<html\> tag.

---

\<html\> **Tag:**

* **Purpose**: The \<html\> tag is the root element of an HTML document. It wraps all the content of the webpage and contains both the \<head\> and \<body\> sections.  
* **Placement**: It follows the \<\!DOCTYPE html\> declaration and encloses the entire content of the HTML document.  
   

---

**The Head Section**

\<head\> **Tag:**

* **Purpose**: The \<head\> section contains metadata and other elements that are not directly visible on the webpage but are crucial for its functionality. This includes links to stylesheets, scripts, and the document's title.  
* **Placement**: It is located inside the \<html\> tag but outside the \<body\> tag.

---

\<title\> **Tag:**

* **Purpose**: The \<title\> tag sets the title of the webpage. This title appears in the browser’s title bar or tab and is important for SEO and bookmarking.  
* **Placement**: It is placed within the \<head\> tag.

---

**The Body Section:**

* **Purpose of the** \<body\> **Element**:  
  * Contains all the content that will be displayed on the webpage.  
  * Anything placed outside the \<body\> tags is not visible on the webpage.

---

* **Basic Structure:**  
  * **Opening Tag:** \<body\> – Marks the beginning of the body content.  
  * **Closing Tag:** \</body\> – Marks the end of the body content.  
  * **Example:**

\<body\> \<\!-- Content goes here \--\> \</body\>

* **Key Points:**  
  * **Content Visibility:** Only the content enclosed within the \<body\> tags will be visible to users.  
  * **Versatility:** You can include various HTML elements inside the \<body\> tag to structure and display different types of content, such as headings, links, images, and forms.  
  * **Structure:** The \<body\> element helps in organizing the content and separating it from other parts of the HTML document, like metadata (typically placed in the \<head\> section.
